<paragraph blockId="36.[189,310,1883,1909]" box="[189,310,1883,1909]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,1883,1909]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,1883,1909]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="36.[189,1399,1930,2027]" lastBlockId="37.[189,1398,267,399]" lastPageId="37" lastPageNumber="38" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
The female of 
<taxonomicName authority="Kuhlmann, 2014" authorityName="Kuhlmann" authorityYear="2014" box="[356,506,1931,1957]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Scrapter" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigritarsis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[356,506,1931,1957]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">S. nigritarsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[512,601,1931,1957]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
can be separated from other species of this group by the combination of the following characters: supraclypeal area and clypeus sparsely but distinctly punctate, mostly finely sculptured and slightly matt (
<figureCitation box="[534,618,2000,2027]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="37.[189,232,1932,1958]" captionTargetBox="[190,1399,558,1887]" captionTargetId="figure@37.[189,1399,558,1888]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="Fig. 19. Scrapter nigritarsis sp. nov., ♀. A. Lateral view. B. Thorax (dorsal view, SEM). C. Head. D. Head (SEM). E. Metasoma (dorsal view). Scale bars: photos: 1 mm, SEM: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3860634" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3860634/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Fig. 19</figureCitation>
C–D), scutum sparsely but relatively coarsely punctate, basal area of propodeum basally largely carinate (
<figureCitation box="[666,776,267,293]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="37.[189,232,1932,1958]" captionTargetBox="[190,1399,558,1887]" captionTargetId="figure@37.[189,1399,558,1888]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="Fig. 19. Scrapter nigritarsis sp. nov., ♀. A. Lateral view. B. Thorax (dorsal view, SEM). C. Head. D. Head (SEM). E. Metasoma (dorsal view). Scale bars: photos: 1 mm, SEM: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3860634" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3860634/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Fig. 19B</figureCitation>
), stigma brown, apical margins of metasomal terga black or only slightly brownish translucent, terga impunctate (
<figureCitation box="[928,1035,302,329]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="37.[189,232,1932,1958]" captionTargetBox="[190,1399,558,1887]" captionTargetId="figure@37.[189,1399,558,1888]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="Fig. 19. Scrapter nigritarsis sp. nov., ♀. A. Lateral view. B. Thorax (dorsal view, SEM). C. Head. D. Head (SEM). E. Metasoma (dorsal view). Scale bars: photos: 1 mm, SEM: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3860634" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3860634/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Fig. 19E</figureCitation>
). The male is characterized by an unmodified antenna, simple and black hind tibia and hind basitarsus (
<figureCitation box="[1042,1152,338,364]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="39.[189,231,1900,1926]" captionTargetBox="[189,1399,523,1854]" captionTargetId="figure@39.[189,1399,522,1855]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="Fig. 20. Scrapter nigritarsis sp. nov., ♂. A. Lateral view. B. Genitalia (dorsal view, SEM). C. Metasoma (dorsal view). D. S7 (dorsal view, SEM). E. S8, apical end (SEM). Scale bars: photos: 1 mm, SEM: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3860636" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3860636/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Fig. 20A</figureCitation>
), almost hairless and impunctate abdominal terga (
<figureCitation box="[532,637,373,399]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="39.[189,231,1900,1926]" captionTargetBox="[189,1399,523,1854]" captionTargetId="figure@39.[189,1399,522,1855]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="Fig. 20. Scrapter nigritarsis sp. nov., ♂. A. Lateral view. B. Genitalia (dorsal view, SEM). C. Metasoma (dorsal view). D. S7 (dorsal view, SEM). E. S8, apical end (SEM). Scale bars: photos: 1 mm, SEM: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3860636" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3860636/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Fig. 20C</figureCitation>
) and form of S7 (
<figureCitation box="[846,956,373,399]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="39.[189,231,1900,1926]" captionTargetBox="[189,1399,523,1854]" captionTargetId="figure@39.[189,1399,522,1855]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="Fig. 20. Scrapter nigritarsis sp. nov., ♂. A. Lateral view. B. Genitalia (dorsal view, SEM). C. Metasoma (dorsal view). D. S7 (dorsal view, SEM). E. S8, apical end (SEM). Scale bars: photos: 1 mm, SEM: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3860636" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3860636/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Fig. 20D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
